b"[![](../../cdshop/cdinfo.jpg)](../../cdshop/index.htm)  \n[Sacred Texts](../../index.htm)  [Hinduism](../index.htm)  [Index](index.htm)\n[Previous](sbe07057.htm)  [Next](sbe07059.htm)\n\n* * *\n\np. 184\n\n# LVI.\n\n1\\. Now then[1] follow the purifying Mantras from all the Vedas.\n\n[LVI. M. XI, 250-260; Y. III, 302-305; Gaut. XIX, 12; XXIV.\n\n1\\. 1 'Now then,' i. e. the previous chapter containing an enumeration of\nsecret sins, an enumeration of the purifying Mantras, by which they may be\nexpiated, follows next. (Nand.)]\n\np. 185\n\n2\\. By muttering them, or reciting them at a burnt-oblation, the twice-born\nare purified from their sins. (They are as follows:)\n\n3\\. The Aghamarsha _n_ a; 4. The Devak _ri_ ta; 5. The Suddhavatis; 6. The\nTaratsamandiya; 7. The Kushma _nd_ is; 8. The Pavamanis; 9. The Durgasavitri;\n10. The Atisha _n_ gas; 11. The Padastobhas; 12. The Vyah _ri_ ti Samans.; 13.\nThe Bharu _nd_ as; 14. The _K_ andrasaman; 15. The\n\n[3. Rig-veda X, 190, 1. (This and the following references are based upon\nNand.'s statements.)\n\n4\\. Va _g_ asaneyi Sa _m_ hita VIII, 13.\n\n5\\. Rig-veda VIII, 84, 7-9.\n\n6\\. Rig-veda IX, 58.\n\n7\\. Va _g_ as. Sa _m_ h, XX, 14-16 (Taitt. \xc3\x82ra _n_ y. X, 3-5).\n\n8\\. The term Pavamanya _h_ in its most common use denotes the ninth book of\nthe Rig-veda, but Nand. here refers it to Taitt. Brahm. I, 4, 8.\n\n9\\. Rig-veda I, 99, 1.\n\n10\\. Sama-veda II, 47-49. Regarding this and the following Samans see also\nBenfey, Ind. Stud. III, 199 seq., Burnell's Index to the \xc3\x82rsheya Brahmana, and\nS. Goldschmidt's remarks in his edition of the \xc3\x82ranyaka Samhita, Transactions\nof the Berlin Academy, 1868, p. 246 seq.\n\n11\\. Sama-veda II, 578-580.\n\n12\\. 'The Vyah _ri_ ti Samans, i. e. bhu _h_ and the four others.' (Nand.) The\nfour others are, bhuva _h_ , sva _h_ , satyam, purusha _h_. See \xc3\x9byagana III,\n2, 10, in Satyavrata Sama _s_ rami's edition of the Sama-veda Sa _m_ hita.\n\n13\\. 'Bharu _nd_ a is the name of certain Samans, twenty-one in number, which\nbegin with the words, yat te k _ri_ shna _h_ _s_ akuna (Rig-veda X, 16, 6).\nThey are contained in the \xc3\x82ra _n_ yagana.' (Nand.) The reading of the last\nword is doubtful. At all events, the verse quoted by Nand. does not occur in\nthe \xc3\x82ra _n_ yagana. It may be that the Samans called Ekavi _ms_ atyanugana are\nmeant, which are found in that work, though they do not contain the verse\nreferred to.\n\n14\\. Sama-veda I, 147.\n\n15\\. \xc3\x82ra _n_ yaka Sa _m_ hita IV, 33, 34, in Goldschmidt's edition, = Rig-veda\nX, 90, 1, 4.]\n\np. 186\n\ntwo Samans called Purushavrata; 16. The Abli _n_ ga; 17. The Barhaspatya; 18.\nThe Gosukta; 19. The \xc3\x82 _s_ vasukta; 20. The two Samans called _K_ andrasukta;\n21. The _S_ atarudriya; 22. The Atharva _s_ iras; 23. The Trisupar _n_ a; 24.\nThe Mahavrata; 25. The Naraya _n_ iya; 26. And the Purushasukta;\n\n2 7. The three \xc3\x82 _g_ yadohas[1], the Rathantara[2], the Agnivrata[3], the\nVamadevya[4], and the B _ri_ hatsaman[5], properly chanted, purify man from\nsin; and if he wishes he may obtain through them recollection of his existence\nin a former life.\n\n* * *\n\n[Next: LVII.](sbe07059.htm)\n\n"